ums = [10,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9,1,0]", "output": "3"}, {"input": "nums = [2,4,6,8,0,1,3,5,7,9]", "output": "8"}], "query": "You are an expert Python programmer. You will be given a question (problem specification) and will generate a correct Python program that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nYou are given an integer array nums of size n containing each element from 0 to n - 1 (inclusive). Each of the elements from 1 to n - 1 represents an item, and the element 0 represents an empty space.\nIn one operation, you can move any item to the empty space. nums is considered to be sorted if the numbers of all the items are in ascending order and the empty space is either at the beginning or at the end of the array.\nFor example, if n = 4, nums is sorted if:\n\nnums = [0,1,2,3] or\nnums = [1,2,3,0]\n\n...and considered to be unsorted otherwise.\nReturn the minimum number of operations needed to sort nums.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: nums = [4,2,0,3,1]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation:\n- Move item 2 to the empty space. Now, nums = [4,0,2,3,1].\n- Move item 1 to the empty space. Now, nums = [4,1,2,3,0].\n- Move item 4 to the empty space. Now, nums = [0,1,2,3,4].\nIt can be proven that 3 is the minimum number of operations needed.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,4,0]\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: nums is already sorted so return 0.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: nums = [1,0,2,4,3]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation:\n- Move item 2 to the empty space. Now, nums = [1,2,0,4,3].\n- Move item 3 to the empty space. Now, nums = [1,2,3,4,0].\nIt can be proven that 2 is the minimum number of operations needed.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nn == nums.length\n2 <= n <= 105\n0 <= nums[i] < n\nAll the values of nums are unique.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def sortArray(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def sortArray(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        def f(nums, k):\n            vis = [False] * n\n            cnt = 0\n            for i, v in enumerate(nums):\n                if i == v or vis[i]:\n                    continue\n                cnt += 1\n                j = i\n                while not vis[j]:\n                    vis[j] = True\n                    cnt += 1\n                    j = nums[j]\n            return cnt - 2 * (nums[k] != k)\n\n        n = len(nums)\n        a = f(nums, 0)\n        b = f([(v - 1 + n) % n for v in nums], n - 1)\n        return min(a, b)\n```\n\nThis solution uses a helper function `f` to calculate the number of operations needed to sort the array with the empty space either at the start or at the end. It then returns the minimum of the two possibilities. The helper function works by counting cycles in the permutation of the array and adjusting for the position of the empty space.", "estimated_date": 1667088000000}